CMSC320 Uber Trends NYC Final Project

Rohan Kumar, Ryan Lam, Emmanuel Benyam

Concern of our study: Joining Ubers extensive club of drivers seems as simple as get a car, get the app and get paid. Although this industry and life changing application creates a quick and convenient opportunity to generate revenue, the process itself isnt without its faults. People that have joined Uber have voiced their experiences and highlight the problem of extensive wait time between customers. Others may have issues of planning out adequate times for driving for Uber due to other job or life constraints.

How we will conduct research: For our study, weve decided to focus our attention on one extremely popular area for Uber in the United States, New York City. We set out to study the trends of Uber pickups that occurred within New York City from January 2015 to June 2015 under various conditions such as location, time of day, day of the week, and various atmospheric conditions. By doing so, we hope to understand an average 24 hour day with Uber and conclude any trends that may assist drivers in being more successful and efficient with their routes. The purpose of this research is to demonstrate to those who want to join Uber as drivers, or current Uber drivers, what conditions may affect their daily lives and understand if working for Uber is worth the investment, time and in general if it corresponds with their schedules.

1.2 Snowfall Versus Uber Pickups

uber_data %>%
  group_by(Snow_Depth = floor(`Snow Depth`)) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=Snow_Depth, y=NumPickups)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity", color="blue", fill="white") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)

In order to get this graph, we will need a pipeline. We first read in our uber_data dataframe and immediately use the group_by method. The group_by method is useful for grouping columns within a dataframe based on certain conditions. In this case, we grouped by the snow depth and took the floor of the values in order to get more organized data. This splits up the data by snow depth.

We then pipe the results into a summarize method which summarizes the number of pickups based on our group_by that we used one line above. The way we used this method was to sum up pick ups based on the different snow depth values. When printed, we will see the x value as snow fall and y values of the sum of all pickups based on snowfall values.

The goal of this plot is to see if there is some sort of correlation between snow depth and number of pickups. From looking at the plot, there is no straight-forward pattern on how snow affects the number of pick ups.

This is due to the fact that most days in New York are not snowing so it makes sense that there is over 10,000,000 pick ups when there were 0 inches of snowfall. What was surprising was a higher rate for when snowfall was around 8 inches. This could be explained by people not wanting to walk to their destinations due to the heavy snow. It can also be explained by the increase of uber uses due to the holiday season. Around Christmas and New years, it is in the middle of winter which might explain why more people need to call Ubers in order to meet up with friends and family for parties/events.

1.3 Number of Pickups Versus Month

#Visualizing different variations of data to understand the frequency of Ubers based on different factors
uber_data %>%
  group_by(Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month")) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = Month, y = NumPickups)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity")+ scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE))
## Warning in (function (dt, year, month, yday, mday, wday, hour, minute, second, :
## System timezone name is unknown. Please set environment variable TZ.

For this graph, we decided to look at the number of pickups from Uber drivers that occur each month. We figured this data would give us an understanding of any relationship that might exist between the number of pickups from Uber and time of the year. Our initial hypothesis was that there would be a higher number of Uber pickups that occurred in the months of January to March due to increasing weather that may encourage people to use Uber. However, based on the diagram above, we noticed that there was a positive correlation between the number of pickups and time of the year with a peak in June. We concluded that this made sense due to the influx of tourists in NYC during the time of summer.

1.6 Number of Pickups based on Visibility

uber_data %>%
  group_by(VisibilityCut=cut(Visibility, breaks = 4), Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month")) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = Month, y = NumPickups, fill = VisibilityCut)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity",position=position_dodge())+ scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE))

This plot gets into the understanding of visibility and its relationship with the number of pickups. There are 4 different colors each representing different amounts of visibility. Furthermore, the data is also split into months of the year - with each month showing its own amounts of visibility.

To understand what this plot represents and provides us it is important to understand what visibility means in this context. Visibility is the amount of miles you can see ahead. This means that a higher visibility rating means it it less foggy and there is less precipitation.The plot reveals that there are more pickups when visibilities are higher as the 7.5,10 group has overwhelmingly larger numbers indicating that there are more business transactions going on on less foggy days.

2.1 Number of Pick ups Versus Holiday

uber_data %>%
  group_by(Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month"), Holiday) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(uber_data, mapping=aes(x = Month, y = NumPickups, fill = Holiday)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", position=position_dodge()) + scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE)) + scale_fill_manual(values = cbp2)

This plot shows the number of uber pick ups based on holidays versus non-holidays. We expected there to be a large influx during the holidays but from looking at this graph, we can see that there is no clear corrleation between holidays versus non-holidays.

The way we plotted this was by using a pipeline. We first used the group_by method and split it by month. Our dataset has a yes/no column that indicates whether or not a day is a holiday or not. We used this parameter to group the dates that were a holiday versus those that were not. We then used the summarize method to obtain the number of pick ups for holidays and non holidays. Lastly, we used the ggplot function to plot the graph out.

Although this graph does not show any correlation, it is useful since it lets us know that holidays do not affect the number of pick ups positively or negatively. A better way to approach this if there was some sort of correlation is to standarize the data and see percent increases instead of raw sums.

The purpose of this plot was to see what time Uber pickups are most prevalent. We first made a new data fram from the existing larger data frame with all of the Uber data. In this new data frame (new_num), we first grouped by Time and Month. In our dataframe, time is represetnted as a number from 0-23 where 0 represents midnight and 23 represents 11:00PM. The data provided to us only had data for the hour which allowed us to use values from 0-23 to represent times.

We then summarized the data based on the sum of number of pick ups by month and time. The months represented in this dataframe is January through June. We then plotted the data using a line graph to show change over time.

Based on the plot, we can see that June around 8:00PM had the highest number of pick ups. We can also see that Janurary around 5:00AM had the least amount of pick ups. Based on this, the best time to be a uber driver can clearly be seen if the driver worked evenings in June. The least profitable time for uber drivers can be seen to be around 5:00AM in January.

3.3 Regression Model Number of Pickups vs Month by Weekdays

uber_data$Weekdays <- as.Date(uber_data$Date)
uber_data$Weekdays <- weekdays(uber_data$Weekdays)

uber_data %>%
  group_by(Month=floor_date(FullDate, "month"), Weekdays) %>%
  summarize(NumPickups=sum(`No. of Pickups`)) %>%
  ggplot(uber_data, mapping=aes(x = Month, y = NumPickups, fill = Weekdays, color = Weekdays)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) + scale_fill_manual(values = cbp2) + geom_smooth(method = lm, aes(fill=Weekdays), se=FALSE, fullrange=TRUE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

This plot shows number of pick ups based on the month by which week day. There are 5 different colored points on this plot and each one represents a different week day. As seen above, we can see the total number of pick ups on Saturday in the month of January was right below 400,000.

To make this plot, we first created a pipe with uber_data. We used the group_by function first and grouped by Month and weekday. This splits our data up based on the month and weekday of the data. We then used a summarize function in order to figure out the amount of pick ups per day per month which we used to plot. Next, we used the ggplot function to create the actual plot. The first parameter indicates our dataset which is uber_data. The next parameter is the aesthetics parameter which has many other parameters within. The most important 2 are the x and y parameters which indicate what values to use for the x and y coordinate. The next parameter that we used was fill which fills the color of the lines based on the weekday.

After this, we wanted physical points on the plot so we added the + geom_point()" parameter. The y axis was in scientific notation which is hard to read so the next parameter is used to place commas in the numerical values. The next parameter just indicates what color range to use with the graphs to make it more visually pleasing. The last parameter is the most important part where we implement a linear regression method which is based on the number of pick ups as well as the week day. On the plot, the linear line is fitted based on the value. This regression shows that the number of pick ups steadily increases for each week day as the month increases.
